1
00:00:05,549 --> 00:00:09,076
Because sometimes
things are lost in translation,

2
00:00:09,076 --> 00:00:11,965
sometimes things are gained
in translation.

3
00:00:11,965 --> 00:00:15,346
And while we are 
on the subject of translation,

4
00:00:15,346 --> 00:00:20,756
it should be noted—
all translation is interpretation.

5
00:00:21,116 --> 00:00:24,181
[Translation | Depth of Understanding]

6
00:00:24,181 --> 00:00:29,411
All translation
is interpretation.

7
00:00:29,411 --> 00:00:31,752
So when
you read something,

8
00:00:31,752 --> 00:00:34,852
and it says, “Guru Mahārāj
wrote this in Sanskrit,

9
00:00:34,852 --> 00:00:37,732
or Guru Mahārāj
wrote this in Bengali.”

10
00:00:37,732 --> 00:00:40,169
And than there’s 
a translation,
 

11
00:00:40,169 --> 00:00:43,169
that translation 
is based upon

12
00:00:43,169 --> 00:00:47,879
the capacity of the translator
to render

13
00:00:47,879 --> 00:00:51,559
what they were able
to extract from that.

14
00:00:51,559 --> 00:00:55,922
Don’t take it literally
these are the words of Guru Mahārāj.

15
00:00:55,922 --> 00:00:59,585
They are the words
of a translator, an interpreter.

16
00:00:59,585 --> 00:01:01,474
Someone who saw this word
 

17
00:01:01,474 --> 00:01:03,629
and on the basis of their capacity 
is saying,

18
00:01:03,629 --> 00:01:07,489
“I think it means this
in my language.”

19
00:01:07,489 --> 00:01:10,693
But it would be a mistake 
to think

20
00:01:10,693 --> 00:01:12,933
that these are
Guru Mahārāj’s words.

21
00:01:12,933 --> 00:01:15,471
They are not.
That’s why we find

22
00:01:15,471 --> 00:01:18,347
when we read books
that are in translation,

23
00:01:18,347 --> 00:01:21,355
that weren’t spoken
by Śrīla Guru Mahārāj

24
00:01:21,355 --> 00:01:24,608
in English, 
they don’t sound like him.

25
00:01:24,608 --> 00:01:26,940
They sound
like something else.

26
00:01:26,940 --> 00:01:31,396
And in this regard, once
one book was being translated

27
00:01:31,396 --> 00:01:36,407
and it just so happened
that Śrīla Guru Mahārāj

28
00:01:36,407 --> 00:01:42,017
spoke about the very thing
that was being translated that morning.

29
00:01:42,017 --> 00:01:46,280
So, I met with him in the afternoon
cause I was a little concerned.

30
00:01:46,280 --> 00:01:50,001
And I said,
“What they are translating …

31
00:01:50,001 --> 00:01:54,663
what you said this morning,
that’s not what they’re translating.”

32
00:01:54,663 --> 00:01:56,476
And, but his answer
surprised me.

33
00:01:56,476 --> 00:02:00,734
He said, 
“Is anything coming through?”

34
00:02:00,734 --> 00:02:04,499
and I said, “Yes, definitely
something’s coming through.”

35
00:02:04,499 --> 00:02:07,381
He said,
“Then it has its value.”

36
00:02:07,381 --> 00:02:11,694
He said, “Just as when
you speak on a śloka,

37
00:02:11,694 --> 00:02:12,954
you are going 
to give a class,
 

38
00:02:12,954 --> 00:02:15,427
and you are going
to speak on a śloka.

39
00:02:15,427 --> 00:02:19,071
According to your ability
you extract something,

40
00:02:19,071 --> 00:02:21,011
and you’re sharing that.”

41
00:02:21,011 --> 00:02:25,009
He said, “It doesn’t mean
that having done that

42
00:02:25,009 --> 00:02:28,719
that you have exhausted
all the possible things

43
00:02:28,719 --> 00:02:30,489
that can be said 
about that.”
 

44
00:02:30,489 --> 00:02:34,129
But according to your ability,
your capacity,

45
00:02:34,129 --> 00:02:37,097
you extracted something 
and shared that.

46
00:02:37,097 --> 00:02:42,677
And hopefully we are talking
about inspired representation.

